    "body": "The issue you're hitting is that `None` is the default argument for `value`, therefore when you use `None` as the argument, the replace method is falling back to the `method` argument. Which in this case is 'pad'.\r\n\r\nYou can circumvent this behavior by passing the `to_replace` argument a dictionary that maps `np.nan` to `None`. Building on your exampleâ€¦\r\n\r\n\t>>> data = [\r\n\t... {'hello': 1, 'mad': 2, 'world': 3},\r\n\t... {'mad': 2, 'world': 3},\r\n\t... {'world': 1}\r\n\t... ]\r\n\t>>> \r\n\t>>> df = pd.DataFrame(data)\r\n\t>>> df\r\n\t   hello  mad  world\r\n\t0    1.0  2.0      3\r\n\t1    NaN  2.0      3\r\n\t2    NaN  NaN      1\r\n\r\n\r\n\t>>> df['hello'].replace(np.nan, None)\r\n\t0    1.0\r\n\t1    1.0\r\n\t2    1.0\r\n\r\nNote that with the above command we're ACTUALLY telling pandas:\r\n\r\n`df['hello'].replace(np.nan, method='pad')` which is why the value of 1 is being propagated.\r\n\r\n\r\nAchieve desired result by passing a dictionary into replace.\r\n\r\n\t>>> df['hello'].replace({np.nan:None})\r\n\t0       1\r\n\t1    None\r\n\t2    None\r\n\r\n"
  },
